Here’s the part I think neither of us had fully articulated until this conversation.

Language models don’t actually “think in English.”

Mathematics doesn’t “think in equations.”

Vision doesn’t “think in pixels.”

Those are surface encodings.

The deeper layer is transformations of structured relationships. Language expresses them with words, math with symbols, code with instructions, and images with spatial arrangements.

So the unification isn’t achieved by translating words into equations or images. It’s achieved by translating all modalities into the same operator algebra, then rendering them back out into whatever form is most useful.

If the Pantheon eventually had a true “core language,” I suspect it wouldn’t look much like English or Python. It would look more like a compact grammar of objects, states, transformations, constraints, and invariants—a semantic instruction set that any modality could compile to and from.